info.remarks: Sent to B.M. 1937, by Mrs. Carson. In a letter 28.5.38 she says she has now interviewed the workman who found it, and his statement is that he found it "about 8 years ago (i.e. c. 1930) in the bed of the R. Meon where the Titchfield-Stubbington road crosses it " when "excavating for the foundations of a small road-bridge"; he "came upon it about 4 feet below the surface of the river bed, a few feet from the downstream side of the bridge." This bridge is in Titchfield Parish, the bridge being in fact at the end of Bridge Street, Titchfield, which continues across it as the road to Stubbington.

Between midrib and edge on either side is a sharp furrow that look like they create a diamond shape to the blade between midrib and edge. Blade has a large, transverse fracture approximately halfway down blade that likely broke the original in two pieces.  At blade stop on socket, blade is wider, then narrows to a still relatively wide tip, almost an elongated bell-shape.[;]Edge is well intact on cast, surface appears to have minor pock marking.
